Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany
Foreword
The Lima Declaration, adopted in 1977, stresses that the courts of auditors are authorized to audit all public finances.
The statement requires that the courts of auditors have the power to examine the tax collection as much as possible.
The organisation of the European Supreme Audit Institutions (EUROSAI) considers taxes to be an important part of public revenue.
The thematic focus of the Sixth EUROSAI Congress, which took place in Bonn in 2005, was the audit of public revenues by the courts of auditors.
One of the most important steps towards optimising the audit work of a Court of Auditors is the development of a specific strategy for the audit of public revenue.
This is particularly true of taxes as the largest source of public revenue with a high risk of default.
As national economies are increasingly interlinked and interdependent, a situation may arise where national audit bodies can only carry out their audit work in cooperation with other states' audit bodies.
As an example, the examination of internationally organised fraud can be considered, which can lead to significant losses of revenue in many states.
The fight against such crimes requires cooperation between the authorities.
Audit bodies in this area must be prepared to cooperate closely with each other.
The idea for an audit of the turnover tax and the MIAS system was developed at the 6th EUROSAI Congress in Bonn, which was carried out in cooperation between the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic and the German Federal Court of Auditors.
In the course of thorough preparation, the Audit Bodies involved first had to familiarize themselves with the legal framework and procedures of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany.
On the basis of the analysis of the available information, we made the selection of the subject-matter for the examination planning.
Achieving the efﬁcient and effective management of VAT is a long-standing problem and individual states (in particular the EC member states) are looking for solutions to improve the system, simplify the collection of VAT and create greater transparency in this area.
We are convinced that the results of our audit will not only contribute to improving the work of the financial administration, but will also provide the basis for a proposal for an improved system of international exchange of information.
Report on the results of the parallel audit of the administration of VAT of the Czech Republic and Germany
Introduction
File number: CZ) 06 / 27 (DE) VIII 2 - 2005 - 1215
Subject-matter of the examination:
(CZ) administration of VAT after the accession of the Czech Republic to the European Union
(de) examination of administrative cooperation in the field of VAT in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and 1925 / 2004
The aim of the Commission's audit is to:
(CZ) the objective of the audit in the Czech Republic was to examine the procedures applied by the Financial Administration in the area of VAT after the integration of the Czech Republic into the common internal market of the European Community (hereinafter "the EC") with the free movement of goods and services and the use of mias1, in particular the control of the claim of VAT exemption for intra-Community deliveries.
(de) The objective of the audit was to examine the system of intra-Community VAT control with a focus on mutual assistance in the area of VAT in accordance with the above-mentioned regulations.
As a result of the audit, weaknesses should be identified and recommendations made to remedy them.
The audits were carried out jointly by the Court of Auditors of the Czech Republic ("nkú") and the Federal Audit Court ("BRH") of the Federal Republic of Germany on the basis of an agreement concluded on 8 June 2006.
The cooperation focused on the review of selected business transactions between entrepreneurs of the Czech Republic and the Federal Republic of Germany, the exploitation of information obtained by international administrative assistance between the financial authorities and the comparison of the turnover tax management systems in the two states.
A joint final report on the results of the audits was prepared in accordance with European Guideline No. 31 for the implementation of INTOSAI audit standards.
The period under review covered the period from 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005.
Summary of the results and evaluation of the parallel audit
The parallel audit of the VAT administration in the Czech Republic and Germany was carried out on the basis of an agreement between the two courts of auditors.
In addition to the exchange of information in accordance with Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 and Commission Regulation (EC) No 1925 / 2004, other closely related aspects have also been examined, such as the registration of tax evacuees, tax returns and summary notifications.
The audit also covered the legal situation of cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach and the comparison of statistical data.
When comparing the systems of VAT administrations in the two states, differences were found in the following areas:
1) registration for VAT purposes.
While in Germany, business owners are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic, among others, the essential criterion for registration is to exceed the turnover threshold laid down in the Turnover Tax Act.
In the Czech Republic, tax payers receive only one tax identification number, which they also use for intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, the tax payer receives a tax number that applies only to domestic sales for the purposes of sales tax.
If the German tax-resident wants to make intra-Community transactions, he must apply for the issuance of a special identification number, the so-called USt-IdNr.
As problems arise from the different registration procedures, the rules should be harmonised within the EC (see 4.1).
2) cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach.
In the Czech Republic, cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach is tax-free, but there is a right to deduct VAT.
In Germany, as far as the route passes through Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT.
Efforts should be made at EC level to unify the situation in accordance with Article 393 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common turnover tax system (see 4.2).
3) tax returns.
While in the Czech Republic, tax-deductible VAT returns are only required for tax periods of less than one year (month or quarter), tax payers in Germany (monthly or quarterly)
Pre-Registration of VAT and a declaration of VAT after the end of the calendar year.
In contrast to the Czech Republic, tax payers in Germany have to file VAT pre-registrations electronically.
The introduction of the right to electronic sales tax returns in the Czech Republic would improve the efficiency of the Czech Financial Administration (see 4.3).
4) summary messages.
While tax payers in the Czech Republic have to submit their summary reports to the tax authorities (FÄ), German tax payers have to submit the summary reports to ClO2.
Accordingly, FÄ in the Czech Republic will have access to the information from the summary reports immediately after they have been submitted.
The information from the summary reports is only available to Germans after they have been processed by the CLO.
To combat VAT fraud, updated information on intra-Community transactions is needed as soon as possible.
The monthly submission of summary messages would shorten the period between the date of sales and the update of MIAs data.
This would allow for a timely examination of taxation in the Member State of the acquirer (see 4.4), but only if all EC Member States introduce the same time limits.
5) international exchange of information in the area of sales tax.
In the case of requests for information, the Czech clo will monitor compliance with the three-month deadline.
The German clo does not monitor the processing times.
As a result, the German Financial Administration has carried out a significantly lower percentage of requests for information within the specified period.
Because of these problems, the BRH has recommended to the German clo a constant monitoring of the deadlines (see 4.6).
6) risk management.
Each of the two Member States is to develop its own risk management system (RMS) with corresponding strengths and weaknesses.
The ncú and the BRH point out that an effective RMS cannot be developed by one Member State alone.
Successful criteria, elements or approaches of an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in all EC Member States. Otherwise, fraudsters will choose the Member State with the weakest RMS (see 5.).
As part of the cooperation, the two courts of auditors examined selected cases of intra-Community transactions carried out between Czech and German tax entities.
Of these, 31 cases were jointly reviewed using CLO's legal options, where there were doubts about the correct taxation or the suspicion of VAT fraud.
The courts of auditors noted the following:
In some cases, the FÄ used the information obtained in the international exchange of information and redefined the tax liability of the tax payers concerned.
In these cases, tax evaders had either unlawfully claimed the VAT exemption or failed to declare the purchase of goods in their VAT returns.
In some cases, the FÄ could not use the information obtained in the exchange of information because it was incomplete or incomprehensible.
In other cases, the information could not be used because of different legal regulations in the two Member States.
In some cases, the financial administration of another Member State refused to provide the requested information.
A number of cases have been revealed where tax evaders misstated sales in their summary reports.
As a result, the data in the MIAS were correspondingly incorrect, so that the officers (the FÄ) had to determine in these cases (see 6).
