An entrepreneur with a legal domicile, registered office or establishment in the Czech Republic, whose turnover exceeds CZK 1,000,000 in the last 12 consecutive calendar months, will be paid on the first day of the third month after the month in which he has exceeded the threshold (Section 94 (1) of Law no. 235 / 2004 Coll., on turnover tax; hereinafter "law no. 235 / 2004").
The person concerned must apply for registration within 15 days of the end of the month in which he has exceeded the registration threshold.
Current legislation does not allow the retroactive registration of a tax payer if he has exceeded the registration deadline.
An entrepreneur with a legal domicile, registered office or a permanent establishment in the Czech Republic, who provides VAT-related services or benefits exempt from VAT with the right to deduct VAT, must register for VAT even if his turnover does not exceed CZK 1 million, but he meets other conditions specified in Law no. 235 / 2004.
An entrepreneur with a legal domicile, registered office or a permanent establishment in the Czech Republic, who does not meet the requirements set out in the law, may voluntarily apply for registration for VAT.
Upon receipt of the registration application by the local financial officer, the registration process begins in accordance with Law no. 337 / 1992.
If you want to register voluntarily for VAT, you must indicate in your application the deadline date from which you apply for registration as a VAT resident.
The Financial Officer must examine the information provided by the entrepreneur, i.e. the completed application for registration with all assets.
If he has doubts about the information provided, he must ask the applicant to explain, supplement or substantiate the information provided.
If the financial officer has verified that the entrepreneur meets the conditions for registration, he must give a written notification of the registration and the allocation of a tax number.
In the Communication, the Financial Officer must indicate the date of entry into force of the VAT registration and the tax assessment period.
The taxation period is the calendar quarter, unless the entrepreneur's turnover for the previous calendar year has reached the amount of at least CZK 10,000,000.
If this is the case, the assessment period is the calendar month.
An entrepreneur whose turnover in the preceding calendar year has reached at least CZK 2,000,000 is entitled to choose the calendar month as a period of taxation and has to inform the financial officer of this change.
The issue of a tax number in the registration notice is always constitutive.
The tax payer has to provide the tax number for each communication (including payments) with the financial officer, as well as in cases where a special law requires it (e.g. law No. 235 / 2004, concerning the preparation of tax documents) 3.
The tax number contains the coding "CZ" and a basic component in the form of a general identification sign.
In the case of natural persons, this is the number of the birth certificate or another general identification mark, as far as a special law determines it. In the case of legal persons, the general identification mark is the company identification number (in accordance with the provisions of Section 33 (12) of Law no. 337 / 1992).
If the Entrepreneur has not complied with his obligation despite a request from the financial officer, the local financial officer has to register him ex officio.
A communication will also be issued to the tax payer.
In the Czech Republic, every entrepreneur authorised to do business receives a tax number for any type of tax at the time of their first registration.
This also applies to registration as a VAT payer.
In accordance with Law no. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, in the event of non-compliance with the law on the registration of the turnover tax, the Financial Officer may require that the tax payer obtain up to 10% of the proceeds of the tax-related turnover, which the person concerned has unlawfully made without taxation, for the period from the date on which the entrepreneur should have been registered as a tax payer, until the date on which on which the registration as tax payer was made by order of the Financial Officer (§ 98 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004).
The payment of the amount set in this way is considered to be a tax payment within the meaning of Section 98 (3) of Law no. 235 / 2004, i.e. it is not a fine or penalty.
If the legal requirements are met, the registration of a tax payer can be deleted for two reasons:
1)
Cancellation of the registration at the request of the tax payer, i.e. mainly for the reason that the turnover does not reach the registration threshold (section 106 (1) of Law No. 235 / 2004).
A tax payer can request the cancellation of his registration at the earliest one year after the effective date specified in the registration notice.
2) Cancellation of the registration ex officio (section 106 (7) of Law No. 235 / 2004), if: a) The tax resident did not perform for 12 consecutive months and did not inform the Financial Officer of the reasons for this, b) the tax resident did not fulfil his obligations under Law No. 235 / 2004, C) the previous tax resident did not meet the requirements for tax protection any more fulfilled.
B) tax evaders without legal domicile, place of business or premises in the Czech Republic a person registered for tax purposes in another Member State and in the Czech Republic does not have a legal domicile, place of business or establishment, or a tax eventer who provides services in the Czech Republic and has to file a tax return and pay taxes for such services or supplies in accordance with Section 108 of Law no. 235 / 2004 ("non-resident entrepreneur")) will be tax-deductible with the provision of the service in question.
He must file an application for registration with the Prague 1 Company no later than the day of the delivery in question.
He is obliged to indicate in this application all UST identification numbers assigned to him in other Member States or third countries.
If a non-resident entrepreneur applies for registration later than on the day of the first tax-deductible performance in the Czech Republic, the Prague 1 company will have to register him retroactively, as he became subject to VAT in accordance with Law No. 235 / 2004 on the day of the first tax-deductible performance in the Czech Republic.
In the event of a retroactive registration, the Prague 1 company shall require the relevant companies to provide proof of performance (invoices or written explanations).
If a non-resident entrepreneur requests registration in the Czech Republic before performing a service for the first time, the company Prague 1 has to request the presentation of the contract documents which provide the basis for the service.
As of December 31, 2004, 473 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered with FA Prague 1, 124 of them from Germany. As of December 31, 2005, a total of 951 non-resident entrepreneurs were registered, 233 of them from Germany.
In accordance with the provisions of section 106 (9) of Law no. 235 / 2004, the Financial Officer is authorized to delete the registration of a non-resident entrepreneur as of 31 January of the following calendar year if he does not accept the obligation to file tax applications or declarations and to pay taxes.
When examining the ncú, it emerged that in the event of a tax return by mail sent abroad on January 25, that is, according to the mandatory deadline for filing a tax return, this declaration has not yet been received by the Fa until January 31.
In cases where these facts, which are relevant for the possibility of cancellation of registration, become known to the Fa later than 31 January, the cancellation of the registration of the non-resident entrepreneur for VAT in the Czech Republic in the calendar year in question is no longer possible.
Registration of tax payers in Germany
In accordance with the provisions of the Tax Code (§ § 137, 138 AO), each business operation must be registered with the municipality and / or the competent tax office.
This registration must be made no later than one month after commencement of business activities.
The municipality will forward the application to the tax authorities.
If the competent tax office finds that a business activity has been started but not notified, it can also register the tax payer ex officio retrospectively.
Tax payers in Germany, regardless of whether they are resident or non-resident, are required to register for zwekke VAT if they meet the requirements of Section 2 of the German VAT Act (UStG).
This does not depend on the amount of turnover achieved.
There is no voluntary registration in Germany.
Special responsibility lies with foreign entrepreneurs.
For example, the chemnitzsüd company is responsible for those entrepreneurs who are based in the Czech Republic.
On 30 April 2004, 295 Czech entrepreneurs were registered with the company; on 1 March 2006, 1,050 Czech entrepreneurs were registered there.
According to the BRH, these authorities, with special powers, refused to register so-called false self-employed persons residing in the new Central and Eastern European Member States of the EC.
Since the free movement of workers is still restricted after the accession of these ten states to the EC, these self-employed people tried to circumvent these restrictions by setting up their own business.
These (sham) self-employed persons do not fulfil the conditions for recognition as entrepreneurs specified in § 2 UStG, since they are usually dependent on a single client, who determines their working time and the type of work execution.
In order to be registered, the entrepreneur must fill out a questionnaire from the relevant Fa and provide information on the company and the business activities carried out.
The questionnaire is a binding form for all FÄ in Germany.
It is processed either in special organisational units within the FÄ or in the organisational units generally responsible for tax assessment.
With the help of this imprint, a risk assessment is carried out for the individual tax payer before the allocation of a tax number.
The structure of the tax number for domestic transactions is based on certain requirements:
The first three digits are the identification number for the relevant Fa, the following three (or four) digits indicate which department is responsible within the Fa, the following five (or four) digits are the identifying feature for the tax payer, the last digit is always a control digit.
If an entrepreneur wants to participate in intra-Community trade, he needs a VAT ID number in order to be able to make tax-free intra-Community deliveries.
This will be allocated by the clo on request if the Entrepreneur is registered in Germany for VAT purposes.
The VAT ID number is automatically allocated by the CLO if the tax payer declares intra-Community deliveries in his VAT pre-registration or in his annual sales tax declaration.
The Ust Id number consists of the country code (DE) and a sequence of nine digits.
The registration of an entrepreneur can be deleted: 1. On request (e.g. if he stops doing business), but only after the completion of all tax transactions (assessment of all financial years) or 2. If the financial administration determines that he no longer runs a business.
As a rule, the validity of the VAT ID number depends on the validity of the VAT number.
In these cases, the FÄ must inform the CLO of the cancellation of the VAT number so that the validity of the VAT ID number can be terminated at this time.
According to the Turnover Tax Act (§ 19 (1) UStG), domestic tax-payers do not have to pay VAT in the following cases: 1. The turnover of the previous calendar year plus the resulting turnover tax did not exceed the amount of 17,500 €and 2. Will probably not exceed the amount of 50,000 €in the following year.
The so-called small business owners are not entitled to charge VAT to other entrepreneurs, nor to deduct VAT.
Although they do not have to pay a turnover tax, small business owners are obliged to register with the tax office and submit an annual turnover tax return.
A small business owner can declare the non-application of § 19 (1) UStG.
This declaration is binding for the following five years.
He may then charge the VAT and deduct the VAT.
Non-residents can appoint a fiscal representative (§ 22a UStG).
The prerequisite for this is that you only make tax-free sales and waive the deduction of VAT.
The fiscal representative meets the tax requirements of the foreign entrepreneur, so that he does not have to register for VAT purposes.
The invoices state that a fiscal representative has been appointed.
Comparison and evaluation
The situation in the two states is different.
While in Germany entrepreneurs are registered regardless of the amount of their turnover, in the Czech Republic the first requirement for registration (among others) is to exceed the threshold specified in the Turnover Tax Act.
If an entrepreneur does not exceed this threshold, he can register voluntarily.
The registration procedure in Germany is standardised, but differences can occur due to different organisational structures in the individual federal states.
In the Czech Republic, the tax collector receives a tax number at the time of his first registration for any tax.
In the case of its registration for VAT, this tax number also applies to intra-Community transactions.
In Germany, an entrepreneur who registers for VAT purposes receives a tax number exclusively for domestic sales.
If the German entrepreneur wants to carry out intra-Community transactions, he has to apply specifically for the allocation of a VAT ID number.
Both nkú and BRH noted that the German two-tier registration system in other Member States, such as the Czech Republic, which provides a single identification number for both national VAT registration and intra-Community transactions, can lead to significant misunderstandings.
On the other hand, the two-tier system allows for retroactive (national registration) in cases where the tax payer does not register his business with the municipality or the relevant Fa.
This retroactive registration allows a true tax assessment for previous tax periods, in particular an accurate estimate of the VAT liability.
As the different registration procedures lead to problems, the rules for the whole of the EC should be harmonised.
The German Parliament recently decided to introduce a tax identification number.
This is to be allocated by the Federal Central Office for taxes to every natural person after birth.
This number is valid for life for natural persons resident in Germany.
If a natural person starts a business, the responsible company applies for a commercial tax identification number, which serves as a VAT identification number.
In the future, there should therefore be no delay between the national registration of a tax payer and the allocation of the VAT ID number.
Work on the implementation of an IT procedure for the management of numbers has not yet been completed.
Cross-border passenger transport by bus and coach
The legal regulations in the Czech Republic
According to the provisions of Section 70 of Law no. 235 / 2004, since 1 May 2004, passenger transport between Member States and between Member States and third countries in the Czech Republic has been exempt from VAT and is entitled to deduct VAT.
The exemption from VAT applies even if the transport is carried out by persons registered as tax evaders in other Member States or by foreigners who are tax evaders at home.
The return journey is considered to be a separate transport operation.
If non-resident entrepreneurs in the Czech Republic do not carry out any economic activity other than cross-border passenger transport by bus, they are not obliged to register in the Czech Republic as a tax payer.
Cross-border passenger transport in the Czech Republic has been exempted from VAT in accordance with the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic, Annex V, chapter 5 (1) (b).
"for the purpose of applying Article 28 (3) (b) of Directive 77 / 388 / EEC, the Czech Republic may, in accordance with point 17 in Annex F of the Directive, maintain the exemption for cross-border passenger transport either until the condition of Article 28 (4) of the directive is met or until the same exemption is applied by any of the current Member States."
The legal regulations in Germany
According to Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006, as implemented in Germany by § 3b (1) UStG, a transport service is carried out where the transport is carried out.
Accordingly, German taxation does not distinguish between domestic and cross-border passenger transport.
Only the domestic part of the transport service is tax-exempt in Germany.
Nor does German taxation distinguish between resident and non-resident (bus) entrepreneurs.
If a non-resident tax-resident transports a person through Germany, the portion of the transport due to Germany is considered a tax-deductible transport.
Before providing its services in Germany, the non-resident entrepreneur must report his intention to provide passenger transport services to the relevant company.
It registers it for tax purposes (Compare 4.1.2) and issues a special certificate for each bus named in the tax payer's application.
The entrepreneur must state his tax-deductible transport services in a German VAT return.
As of March 1, 2006, 741 Czech bus operators were registered with the Chemnitz-Süd company.
If the transport service is provided for a domestic entrepreneur, the non-resident tax payer does not have to pay the VAT himself to the company.
In its place, the domestic customer of the services must pay the VAT to the Tax Office and the net amount charged to the non-resident tax resident, which is referred to as the "transfer of the tax liability" and is in accordance with article 196 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC.
In addition to the registration by a non-resident tax resident and his income tax return, the German tax administration has several means to verify the accuracy of the tax return with regard to tax-related passenger transport:
Mobile customs control groups check the certificates of buses registered abroad, which are used to transport passengers through Germany.
After each inspection, the mobile control groups submit an inspection protocol to the relevant Fa.
If the bus driver does not have a valid certificate, the mobile control group can ask the bus driver to pay the VAT before continuing the journey.
The non-resident tax payer can deduct the VAT paid in this way from the tax liability stated in his VAT return.
If the FA has doubts about the accuracy of a VAT return, it may order an audit to be carried out in the Fa, or may use the means of mutual assistance referred to in Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 (see point 4.6).
Even if the foreign tax payer refuses to pay the legally established VAT, the FA can request assistance in accordance with Council Directive 76 / 308 / EEC.
The BRH considers these means of administrative assistance in tax matters to check the VAT return or the compliance with the tax law by a non-resident bus operator to be too expensive in relation to the small amount of VAT on tax-exempt passenger transport.
In particular, the examination of the books of a non-resident tax resident causes disproportionately high costs for the tax resident himself and for the financial administration.
The latter must examine the foreign books, which requires not only knowledge of the foreign language, but also of the foreign accounting principles.
Accordingly, such an examination will require a higher amount of time than a resident tax resident, although the examination will be limited to the passenger transport carried out in Germany.
On the other hand, the non-resident tax resident must not only accept the audit rights of his national financial administration, but also those of the other Member States where he carries out passenger transport there.
In addition, for each Member State in which even a single passenger transport is carried out, the tax payer must comply with all existing tax law requirements in the various languages and on the basis of the forms of the financial administrations of the EC Member States concerned.
The correct taxation of cross-border passenger transport thus leads to a disproportionate administrative burden.
Comparison and evaluation
The legal situation is different in the two states.
In the Czech Republic, passenger transport between different EC Member States as well as between Member States and third countries is exempt from VAT under the Act of Accession of the Czech Republic.
In Germany, the transport service is subject to VAT in accordance with the route covered by the German state.
If a non-resident tax payer provides such a transport service for the first time, he must first notify the relevant Fa.
This registers the tax payer who has to declare the tax-deductible portion of the transport service in a tax return in Germany.
The law enforcement in Germany is very time-consuming.
At least three out of four Czech tax evacuees registered with the Chemnitz-Süd Company have passenger transport as a business purpose.
The amount of tax in question is quite low in relation to the administrative burden.
Member States - which levy VAT in accordance with Article 46 of Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006 on the common turnover tax system - have a high administrative burden in relation to the relevant tax revenue.
In order to avoid the disproportionate cost of VAT, cross-border passenger transport should only be subject to tax in one Member State.
This could be the state where the transport begins or where the service provider is located.
Such a form of taxation would require an amendment to Council Directive 2006 / 112 / EC of 28 November 2006.
Sales Tax Returns
Filing and processing of VAT returns in the Czech Republic
Unless otherwise stipulated by the law, the entrepreneur is obliged to submit a VAT return within 25 days of the end of the tax period, even if no tax liability has been incurred, on the form provided by the Ministry of Finance.
The tax liability arises at the end of the period for the delivery of the VAT return. The VAT on the import of goods is excluded from this regulation according to Law No. 235 / 2004. Here, the due date of the tax is determined according to the customs regulations.
If, as a result, there is a claim for reimbursement of above-average deductible taxes, this amount will be refunded to the tax payer within 30 days of setting this deduction, without having to make an application for it.
The deadline is not applied in cases where the financial Officer Starts a Tax Procedure regarding the tax liability of the tax payer.
Pursuant to section 73 (11) of Law no. 235 / 2004, the right to deduct VAT may be asserted at the latest with the regular tax return for the last tax period of the calendar year in which the right to deduct VAT arose.
At the end of this period, the deduction can still be claimed within three years of the end of the tax period in which the claim would have been possible for the first time.
However, this requires the submission of a supplementary VAT return.
An amendment to Act No. 235 / 2004, which entered into force on 1 January 2005, allows the submission of a supplementary VAT return only for the period during which the right to deduct VAT could have been asserted for the first time.
A tax collector must issue a supplementary VAT return if: a) the sum of the corrections leads to an increase in the tax liability, b) he makes corrections which do not change the last known tax liability, but only change the previous information, c) He makes corrections of the VAT rate and the tax liability in accordance with Section 49 of Law No. 235 / 2004.
A tax collector can issue a supplementary VAT return if the sum of the corrections reduces the tax liability.
The tax payer must make the supplementary tax return by the end of the month following the month in which the facts in question were established.
The sales tax return can be issued electronically either via the Internet or by means of a data carrier.
