Filing and processing of VAT returns in Germany
In Germany, a distinction is made between monthly or quarterly VAT pre-registrations and the annual VAT return.
Those tax payers who are obliged to file VAT pre-registrations must nevertheless file an annual VAT return.
Even small business owners, who are not obliged to pay the sales tax, must make an annual sales tax return.
Tax payers are, in principle, obliged to file a VAT advance notification by the 10th day after the end of the calendar quarter in which the turnover tax is generated (§ 18 (2) UStG).
However, if the sales tax liability in the previous year was more than €6,136 or if it is a newly founded company, the entrepreneur is obliged to file monthly sales tax advance registrations no later than the 10th day after the end of the month in question.
The tax payer may also opt to file monthly VAT pre-registration if he has received a refund of €6,136 in the previous year (Section 18 (2a) of the VAT Act).
If the annual turnover tax is not more than 512 €, neither VAT pre-registration nor VAT returns are to be made.
The resulting VAT liability is to be paid 10 days after the end of the tax period.
A refund can lead to a more thorough audit by the financial administration.
(legal) there are no deadlines for the processing of VAT returns and for the refund of VAT overpayments.
In order to receive a timely refund, a security for the refund amount can be offered.
In principle, VAT returns, including reimbursement cases, must be processed quickly.
The German Sales Tax Act allows an extension of these (delivery or payment) deadlines (§ 18 (6) UStG).
The extension of the time limit must be requested separately.
If it is granted, the VAT pre-registration and the corresponding payments may be made one month later. However, in the case of monthly notifications, a special advance payment must be made.
This payment will be offset against the VAT liability established for the pre-registration period of December.
If an error is detected, the entrepreneur must file a corrected VAT pre-registration.
There is no "supplementary" VAT return.
Once the sales tax return submitted to the Tax Office by 31 May of the following year has been submitted, the entrepreneur can no longer correct an incorrect sales tax advance notification, but only the incorrect annual sales tax return.
Corrections of this VAT return to the benefit or disadvantage of the tax payer are possible within four years after the end of the year in which the first VAT return was issued.
At the end of this four-year period, a VAT return can usually only be corrected in cases of frivolous tax cuts or tax evasion.
Tax payers are required to file VAT pre-registrations electronically.
The FÄ can grant exceptions to this rule in order to avoid unfavorable hardships.
The annual sales tax return can be issued either on paper or via the Internet with or without certification.
If the levy is made without certification, the tax payer must also make the declaration on paper and with his personal signature.
If no VAT pre-registrations or declarations are made, the financial administration is entitled to make a rough estimate of the turnover generated by the tax payer.
In the event of a late Levy, the tax payer may be charged a late surcharge (up to 10% of the tax liability or up to an amount of €25,000).
During an earlier examination, the BRH found that the FÄ often do not charge this late surcharge.
In cases where the FÄ charged the late payment, the amount was fixed inconsistently and arbitrarily.
The late surcharge therefore misses its purpose to reduce the average delay, particularly in the submission of the annual sales tax return.
The form of the VAT return contains separate lines of information on the value of intra-Community deliveries or purchases.
There are also separate lines for the provision of services.
Non-taxable sales are to be indicated in a separate line of the sales tax return.
The sales tax returns submitted on paper must either be scanned or electronically recorded by dedicated personnel.
The data of electronically filed tax returns are directly available to the financial administration.
