In the Czech Republic, tax payers must submit their VAT returns no later than 25 days after the end of the tax period.
Depending on the turnover of the tax payer, the tax period is either the calendar quarter or the calendar month.
In Germany, tax payers have to file their advance registrations at the latest 10 days after the end of the calendar quarter or the calendar month, depending on the amount of their tax liability in the previous year.
The annual sales tax declaration must be submitted by 31 May of the following year at the latest.
The right to submit an annual sales tax return has some advantages and disadvantages:
+ after the end of the calendar year, the tax payer can correct the errors in the monthly advance registrations by submitting a single VAT return;
- If the tax payer corrects his information on intra-Community transactions, the correction cannot be assigned to a specific reporting period of the ZM;
- the federal states only compare MIAs data on intra-Community purchases of German tax evaders when the annual sales tax declarations have usually been processed.
According to the registration (see 4.1.3), German entrepreneurs must file a VAT return regardless of the amount of their turnover.
This levy will enable the German Financial Administration to verify compliance with the turnover limit for small business owners.
