In the Czech Republic, the financial administration can only verify the amount of turnover on the basis of the income tax return issued.
In contrast to the current regulations in the Czech Republic, German tax payers are obliged to submit their VAT registration electronically.
The introduction of the right to electronic tax returns in the Czech Republic would increase the efficiency of the Czech Financial Administration.
Summary messages
Submission and processing of summaries in the Czech Republic
In accordance with the provisions of Section 102 of Law no. 235 / 2004, an entrepreneur who supplies goods to a person registered in another Member State for tax purposes must submit summary reports (hereinafter referred to as "ZM").
The value of the delivered goods is always stated in the ZM in Czech currency, according to the Ust-idnr7, the individual tax payers under which they are registered in the other Member State.
Information on services is not provided in the ZM.
The tax payers with a calendar-monthly or quarterly tax period have to hand over the ZM to the local company at the latest on the 25th day after the end of each quarter.
Incorrect data must be corrected in a correction ZM within 15 days of the finding of the error.
Incorrect data in the ZM is always replaced by the data from the correction ZM.
Similar to the tax returns, tax payers can also hand over the ZM electronically.
If a tax collector does not issue a ZM or correction ZM, although he is required to do so under Law No. 235 / 2004, the Financial Officer must ask him to surrender the ZM in question, pointing out the consequences of the non-Levy. In the event of non-monetary compliance, the Financial Officer is authorized to impose repeated fines of up to CZK 2 million, in accordance with section 37 of Law no. 337 / 1992.
The ncú found during its audit that the FÄ mostly did not use its authority to impose fines on its defaulting tax payers.
In particular, the tax payers are not sufficiently motivated to fulfil their obligations when handing over the ZM, as the failure to levy a Zm does not affect the amount of their VAT liability.
In accordance with Section 102 (5) of Law no. 235 / 2004, the Financial Officer is obliged to check the information in the ZM or the amendment, to remove all ambiguities and to use the information to determine the tax liability.
