- the tax payer does not prove the accuracy of the information reported in the ZM (or correction-ZM) and therefore corrects it by submitting a correction-ZM,
- The financial officer has demonstrated the inaccuracy of the information reported by the tax payer in the ZM or correction ZM.
Corrections made by the financial officer, without a correction fee from the tax payer, do not replace the tax worker's right to make a correction, but only lead to the correction of the data in the balance sheet, so that they are up-to-date, complete and accurate.
The data from the ZM will be sent to the Member States concerned.
Only the national financial authority designated for cooperation with the other Member States in the area of VAT may transmit and receive this data.
This is the clo (in the Czech Republic, this function is performed by the Department of International Assistance in the field of VAT in the Ministry of Finance), and the "o _ mctl" message is automatically sent to the CLO from the other Member States.
It contains all incorrect UST IDNr., which were indicated in the transmitted ZM lines.
If the incorrect USt Id number is used in some of the transmitted lines of the ZM or the corrected ZM, an entry in the list of the incorrect USt Id number is made.
The list contains a "notification of doubt regarding USt-IdNr."
The financial officer checks the data and enters the result of the review into the system.
When purchasing goods from another Member State, the tax payer must state this in his VAT return and enter the value of the purchase in the lines of the VAT return specified for this purpose.
The CLO will forward selected cases of differences between the values of the purchases made by the Czech tax payer in its VAT return and the values indicated by the supplier from the other Member State in its ZM for the delivery of goods to the relevant company for examination.
The experts there have to investigate the deviations.
There may then be three different situations:
A) the value indicated by the Czech acquirer in the relevant sections of its VAT return is lower than the value of supplies indicated by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, the financial officer checks the accuracy of the information.
B) The difference is zero.
This situation can result either from a change of the information within the EC (the foreign supplier rectifies his ZM) or from a change of the information in the VAT return (the Czech tax payer, meanwhile, makes a supplementary VAT return on his own initiative).
In this case, it is at the Financial Officer's discretion to verify the accuracy of the information in the sales tax return.
(C) the value of goods purchased from other Member States, as indicated by the Czech tax payer in his VAT return, is higher than the value of their goods delivered by suppliers from other EC Member States.
In this case, it is up to the Financial Officer to verify the accuracy of the information.
After reviewing the differences and clarifying the reasons for their occurrence, the financial officer enters the results of his review into Atis.
These results will be sent to the CLO.
