Comparison and evaluation
In the Czech Republic, tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries to a person registered for VAT in another Member State must hand over a ZM to the local company within 25 days of the end of the calendar quarter.
The FÄ process the ZM and forward the data to the CLO.
The values of intra-Community deliveries reported by tax payers in the CME are compared with the values of intra-Community deliveries reported by the same tax payers in their VAT returns.
The results of the settlement will be taken into account in the tax assessment.
In Germany, tax payers who have made intra-Community deliveries are obligated to pay quarterly ZM within the first 10 days of the following calendar quarter 10.
Since 1 January 2007, the tax authorities have had to submit the ZM electronically to the CLO.
The data from the ZM will only be available to the FÄ after they have been processed by the CLO.
Both in the Czech Republic and in Germany, tax payers in the ZM only specify the supply of goods.
The provision of services is not specified in the ZM. Unlike the Czech FÄ, the German FÄ cannot correct incorrect information in individual lines of the ZM issued.
Because of this limited access to the German MIAs data, incorrect USt Id numbers were not corrected, even if the tax payer communicated the correct USt Id number to the Fa.
The German tax administration does not compare the information on intra-Community deliveries made by German tax evaders in their VAT pre-registrations with the information provided by the relevant ZM.
Differences between the pre-registration data and the ZM are not regularly revealed before the German clo forwards the MIAS data to other Member States.
Based on these findings of the BRH, it is obvious that a comparison would improve the reliability of the MIAS data transmitted.
The data provided by other Member States on the supply of goods to Czech tax payers is compared in the Czech Republic with the data on the purchase of goods specified by Czech tax payers in their VAT returns.
The Czech clo performs the adjustment for each calendar quarter separately.
The most serious cases of deviations will be sent to the FÄ for examination.
Unlike the Czech Financial Administration, the German Financial Administration does not generally examine the taxation of intra-Community acquisitions.
Such general control will only be carried out for tax evaders who are not fully entitled to deduct VAT.
In addition, the German tax administration only controls the taxation of intra-Community purchases of other tax evaders if the RMS produces an audit note or the tax evader has already been selected for an audit.
This procedure relieves FÄ from clarifying the reasons for differences.
On the other hand, the detection of VAT fraud depends on the quality of the RMS.
To combat carousel fraud, updated information on intra-Community purchases must be available as early as possible.
The current system of the ZM, in particular MIAs, provides financial authorities with information that may well be half a year old.
This time delay could be reduced to up to four months if the tax-payers had to hand over monthly ZM.
The monthly levy would only marginally increase the bureaucratic burden, since most tax-payers in the Czech Republic and Germany are already obliged to submit monthly VAT returns or pre-registrations, and ZM does not require more information than for VAT returns or pre-registrations.
In order to avoid bureaucracy, the submission of the ZM could be linked to the submission of the VAT returns or pre-registrations.
However, a monthly levy on ZM would cause more periodic discrepancies between the information on intra-Community deliveries and those on intra-Community purchases and increase the flow of data between CLO.
In 2006, the federal government considered the general introduction of monthly ZM.
The implementation failed because of the concerns of the federal states.
They feared that a monthly transfer of MIAs data to the CLO of other Member States could lead to misunderstandings and confusion.
In order for the commitment to the monthly levy of ZM to be effective, it is necessary to agree on the uniform monthly levy at European level, so that a monthly update of the MIAS data is possible.
