The international exchange of information without prior request is either automatic, structured automatically or in the form of spontaneous information.
Financial officials from other Member States are often provided with information, without prior request, which is important for determining the VAT liability.
In the Czech Republic, all information is collected by the CLO.
The exchange of information between the individual Member States takes place electronically.
"automatic exchange" under Council Regulation (EC) No 1798 / 2003 means the systematic transmission of previously established information to other Member States at regular, pre-determined intervals, without prior request.
"structured Automatic Exchange" means the systematic transmission of previously established information to another Member State without its prior request, once the information in question is available.
The Czech Republic informs the other Member States in the automatic exchange of information on deliveries of new vehicles.
The financial officer receives this information from the pre-printed notification of the delivery of a new vehicle in accordance with Section 19 of Law no. 235 / 2004 and from the copy of the invoice issued.
In processing this form, the Financial Officer will enter the required data in the relevant document and forward it directly to the relevant Financial Directorate employee, where the data will be collected and sent to the CLO for further processing, after which it will be transmitted to the other Member States within the specified period, at the latest within two months of the end of the quarter in which it was obtained.
The Czech Republic also provides information to other Member States on mail-order transactions tax-free in the country of origin, intra-Community transactions that appear to be illegal and potential "missing traders."
This information will be sent to the other Member States by means of a SCAC form in a spontaneous exchange of information.
Implementation of the international exchange of information in Germany
In Germany, the initiative for requests for information and spontaneous exchange of information emanates from the local Fa.
The FÄ will send the completed SCAC 2004 form by e-mail directly to the German CLO, which will forward the scacforms to the foreign CLO.
The FÄ are instructed to write their requests for information or spontaneous information only in German, even the scacforeprint used is unique.
Half of the German requests for information examined by the BRH were submitted in order to ensure the income tax in the other Member State or to prove the tax exemption of intra-Community deliveries from Germany to the other Member State.
If the German clo receives a request for information from another Member State, it will examine whether the value of the supplies specified in the request exceeds the minimum threshold of €15,000.
If there is no reasonable justification for the request, the German clo refuses to provide information on a turnover below the minimum threshold.
In addition, the German clo provides for the translation of the freely worded texts in the SCAC form [(B1-17) or (E)], if they are not written in German or English.
In order to answer the request for information, the CLO directs it to the relevant Fa and refers to the three-month period.
No further deadlines have been set at the various levels of the German financial administration.
Although the German clo has the technical means to monitor compliance with the deadline, it does not have the necessary personnel capacity to remind the FÄ of answering the uncompleted requests for information.
The FÄ will receive the required information by writing to the tax payer or conducting an external audit.
External auditors usually choose between two types of audit: the VAT special audit, which covers all tax-related transactions within a period of several months, or the so-called VAT review, which may only refer to a recent transaction.
With this short and flexible form of Audit, an announcement to the tax payer is not required and it has proved its worth in the investigation of a single turnover.
In the automatic exchange of information, Germany will provide the other Member State with the following information: - on VAT identification number allocated to companies established in other EC Member States - on the refund of the VAT to entrepreneurs established in other EC Member States.
In addition, Germany has decided to provide the other Member States with the following information as part of the structured automatic exchange of information:
A. The supply of new vehicles to entrepreneurs without VAT, B. distance selling (mail order) to other EC Member States not subject to VAT in Germany, C. significant deviations between the purchases reported by a tax payer and the MIAS data transmitted by other Member States, i.e. intra-Community deliveries of goods subject to taxation by the tax payer in Germany, E. potential "missing traders" who have made intra-Community transactions, regardless of whether their VAT number is still valid or has already been deleted, as well as for tax evaders who have made intra-Community deliveries to potential "missing traders" or to customers who have misused a VAT ID number.
Comparison and evaluation
The sending of requests for information or spontaneous information takes place both in the Czech Republic and in Germany on the initiative of the local authorities, who send the corresponding scacforms to the CLO.
While the Czech clo uses bilingual scacforms (Czech-English) and translates information given into English or German, the Germans follow the instructions to write requests for information or spontaneous information on a monolingual form only in German.
The German clo does not produce translations of German texts.
When examining requests for information between the Czech Republic and Germany in the period 1 May 2004 to 31 December 2005, the ncú found that the Czech Financial Administration completed 74.5% of requests for information received within the three-month period, while the requests for information sent to Germany were handled by the German financial administration only in 40.6% of cases within that period.
Although the German clo refers the FÄ to the three-month period, it does not monitor its compliance.
Due to the lack of reminders, a high proportion of frozen requests for information are made.
That is why the BRH has recommended a continuous reminder procedure to the German CLO.
The situation has now changed.
According to the information available to us, the German clo is now reminding the tax authorities to respond to the pending requests for information.
VAT Risk Management
Risk management in the Czech Republic
In the Czech Republic, several organisational units at different levels of the financial administration are involved in risk management in the area of VAT.
Within the Czech Ministry of Finance, the following organisational units are responsible for risk management and the fight against VAT fraud:
The Department of Methodology and economic management of VAT, or its risk management unit, deals with the identification of potential areas of risk for tax revenue and evaluates trends in these risks in domestic and intra-Community trade.
At the national level, the agency coordinates the requirements for the "credibility of VAT returns" criterion and uses the MIAS data to discover possible tax evasions in the context of intra-Community deliveries and acquisitions.
Based on data on the trade balance of the Czech Republic, it evaluates risk-bearing goods, conceptually prepares risk management in the area of sales tax and cooperates in this area with the relevant EC institutions and the other Member States.
The Department for International Mutual Assistance in the area of VAT provides inter alia for the exchange of information, participates in the creation and maintenance of a relevant information database, evaluates the data available in the MIAS system of other Member States, carries out public relations work and is responsible for other forms of intergovernmental assistance within the meaning of Council Regulation (EC) 1798 / 2003.
