Among other things, the tax audit and tax investigation methodology department conducts risk analyses in the context of the methodological management of tax audits, sets priorities for the work planning of financial directorates regarding the selection of cases to be examined, produces risk analyses to combat tax evasion and, in this context, collects information from the financial administration and other sources and makes proposals for measures to combat tax evasion.
Tax investigators are in charge of the financial services. Their tasks include searching for tax evaders and industries that are at risk in terms of the prevalence of tax evasion (e.g. Internet shops, gold, pharmaceutical industry), searching for unregistered tax evacuees (e.g. Internet services, employment services, electronic and print media, etc.), investigating cases of chain fraud and providing information to local financial authorities..
Special audit units have been set up in 12 selected FÄ.
They have a regional competence and, on the basis of appropriate authorisation, carry out tax audits outside the local area of competence of the FÄ.
The need to set up the special audit units resulted from the increase in established new and "improved" forms of tax evasion, particularly in the context of chain transactions.
These special units check according to the needs of tax investigators or focus on tax evaders with specific activities, multinational companies and tax evaders with particularly high turnover.
The following mechanisms for reducing risks in the area of VAT have been integrated into the ATIS system: - The task of "credibility of VAT returns" to assess the risk-bearing nature of tax returns; - the task of "selecting tax beneficiaries to be examined," Selecting tax evaders to be examined on the basis of certain criteria; - the task of "MIAs" to provide tax officials with access to data provided by other EC Member States made possible.
The "MIAs" task allows, among other things, the following: - verification of the validity of the VAT ID number of tax payers from other Member States, - Confirmation of the value of the goods delivered to a Czech tax payer, as stated in the ZM by all suppliers of the tax payer in question from other Member States, - establishment of a list of tax payers who have not submitted ZM, - formal control of the information provided by tax payers in the Czech Republic, before sending this information to other Member States, to draw up a list of tax payers whose VAT returns do not match the information on goods delivered to other Member States with the information in the ZM, to draw up a list of tax payers whose VAT returns do not match the information on the value of goods purchased from other Member States with the information in the ZM of all their suppliers from other Member States 13.
As part of their mission to combat tax evasion, financial officials have access to data from state agencies such as commercial registers, land registry, motor vehicle registers, commercial registers, etc.
More detailed information can be found in Section 4.4.1 submission and processing of summaries in the Czech Republic.
Risk management in Germany
Due to their federal structure, both the federal financial authorities (in particular the CLO) and the financial authorities of the 16 federal states are involved in the development and introduction of an rms in the Federal Republic of Germany.
Although there are joint Development Working Groups, neither the CLO nor the tax administrations of the federal states have a complete set of data.
At the CLO level, the ST i 2 Unit (hereinafter "kiss" - Coordination Unit for Special VAT audits and tax investigations) collects the findings of the audit on fraud in the Opus database.
In cooperation with the countries, the Kiss has set up another database called magic, where the tax authorities can enter and query the names of discovered missing traders or VAT fraudsters.
The Kiss coordinates both related cases of VAT fraud at the national level and cases of cross-border VAT fraud.
The experiences of the KISS are brought into the development of the RMS by their cooperation in the working groups.
In addition, experts from several other organisational units of the CLO and the BMF are also involved.
The formal review of the composition of UStID no. Other Member States, which appear in the ZM of German tax authorities, is carried out at the CLO.
This formal review takes place before the ZM is transmitted to other Member States in order to improve the reliability of the MIAS data and thus its usefulness (see 4.4.2).
The validity of the UST identification number referred to in the ZM is assessed on the basis of the O _ mctl identifiers transmitted by the other Member States (for the procedure of rectification of invalid UST identification number, see also 4.4.2).
In addition, the CLO's RMS is based on MIAs data transmitted by other Member States and generates various types of communications to detect suspected missing traders, using certain characteristics that usually occur in carousel transactions.
The authorities of the federal states are instructed to process these communications and have to report the results of their investigations to the CLO in certain cases.
The BRH's audit has confirmed that all available features must be included in order to conclude with sufficient probability a case of tax fraud (rather than focusing mainly on a company's turnover).
Accordingly, the BRH has recommended to the BMF to work with combinations of different points of reference in the preparation of the communications.
The risk management system should also take into account other factors, such as the payment behaviour of the tax payer, the industry or the company's shareholding.
A second level of risk management exists with the tax authorities of the federal states and focuses on the processing of VAT pre-registrations and annual declarations.
For example, the system creates a list of tax payers who have indicated intra-Community deliveries in their VAT pre-registration or annual declaration.
This list is sent to the CLO for the purpose of monitoring the complete submission of the Zm.
Furthermore, in this type of risk management, the purchases indicated by the tax payer in its annual sales tax return are compared with the data in the MIAS.
The tax administrations of the Federal States avoid a comparison of the quarterly data, because it would result in too many discrepancies, which are due to factors other than tax evasion or tax fraud; e.g.:
- suppliers and purchasers assume different dates for the execution of intra-Community sales;
- different accounting records and tax returns of discounts and discounts.
In addition to comparing the information from the sales tax returns with the MIAS data, many federal states have certain risk management mechanisms based on information in the sales tax returns and certain other indications (e.g. company wording, Age of the owners / partners, number of employees and payment method of the tax payer).
Bavaria has introduced a rules-based risk management system that allows a team of tax fraud specialists ("risk managers") to program their own rules to identify suspected tax fraudsters.
This system is used in the processing of VAT pre-registrations by FÄ.
This will give the relevant Fa the advice of the RMS before the sales tax is set.
Since this system is not capable of learning, risk managers must adapt the rules according to feedback from the FÄ.
Mecklenburg-Western Pomerania has developed an adaptive neural network based on the data of detected backups.
Based on this data, the RMS is able to learn the characteristics of tax evasion.
The system creates a monthly list of tax cases where there is evidence of tax evasion.
On the basis of this list, the competent authorities decide on the examination of the tax evaders in question.
After the audit, the auditors must report their results so that the RMS can learn from the results of the audits it has proposed.
In North Rhine-Westphalia, an adaptive neural network is used in combination with a rules-based fuzzy system.
Based on a lot of data from processed VAT returns and some other evidence, this Neuro-fuzzy system (also known as datamining) calculates how likely it is that a tax payer is entangled in tax fraud.
It then creates a monthly list of suspected tax fraudsters.
On the basis of this list, the FÄ will select the relevant tax payers for consideration and report the audit results to the data centre in question.
The introduction of these three RMS is underway in the federal states.
Since each of these three risk management systems is based on a different approach, the combination of all three anti-fraud systems seems to be a good idea.
It remains to be seen whether the hoped-for effects will materialise during actual use.
Comparison and evaluation
Although it is not possible in this report to deal with the specific criteria of RMS in the Czech Republic and Germany, the ncú and the BRH have found that each Member State has developed its own RMS.
Like the different approaches in the three German states mentioned above, the RMS of each European State has its particular strengths and weaknesses.
There is currently an exchange of experience between the financial authorities of the European Member States on new trends and new models of cross-border VAT fraud.
VAT fraud - particularly carousel fraud - has proved to be not a national problem, but a European one.
The people involved in fraud coordinate their actions not only in one Member State, but in several Member States.
A Member State alone cannot develop an effective RMS.
Successful criteria, components or approaches for an RMS must be exchanged and implemented in each EC member state. If this does not happen, fraudsters choose the Member State with the weakest RMS for their crimes.
The tax losses caused by pan-European VAT fraud do not necessarily affect the Member State in which the initiator is based.
Any other Member State involved in the fraud may be affected.
That is why a European exchange of experience on the RMS should take place.
