1.
According to the MIAS data, in the third quarter of 2004, a Czech tax collector purchased goods worth €60,500 From a German tax resident.
When the Czech Tax Collector declared a purchase of only €29,869, the Czech Financial Administration sent a request for information to Germany in order to verify the value of the goods delivered.
In its reply to the Czech request for information, the German tax payer in question stated that in the second quarter of 2004 the Czech business partner had delivered goods worth €27,381, in the third quarter goods worth €31,997 and in the fourth quarter goods worth €10,276.
In addition, it emerged from the reply that the VAT ID number of the German tax payer was not valid until 28 September 2004. However, the German clo had accepted another application from the German tax payer and moved forward the validity of the VAT ID number retroactively to 1 May 2004.
The German tax authority corrected the Zm.
On the basis of this information, it was a (intra-Community) purchase of goods by the Czech tax payer.
In a request to the competent tax office in the Czech Republic, the ncú found that in 2004 the Czech tax resident had issued supplementary VAT returns for the individual (under-YEAR) tax periods during which he declared a higher value of purchases from other Member States and at the same time requested the deduction of VAT from purchases from other Member States.
On the basis of these additional VAT returns, the responsible officer of the Czech tax office could not clearly determine whether the declared purchases also included the value of the deliveries of the above-mentioned German supplier.
In response to a request for information from the nkú, the BRH found that the German supplier had been registered as a tax payer in September 2003.
At the time of registration, however, he had not applied for the allocation of a VAT ID number, but only a tax number that was valid exclusively for Germany.
Although it is usually not possible in Germany to assign a tax payer a VAT ID number retroactively, in 2006 the responsible person in charge of the German Financial Administration did so retroactively as of 1 May 2004.
The German clo grants a VAT ID number retroactively if the German entrepreneur did not cause the delayed allocation; for example, if the CLO caused the delay after the application of the tax payer to issue a VAT ID number.
In this case, the CLO issues the VAT ID number retroactively, because the contractor does not need a valid VAT ID number for an intra-Community delivery according to § 6 UStG.
Conversely, a German acquirer does not need the (valid) VAT ID number of its supplier to explain the intra-Community acquisition.
Because of these procedural differences between the Member States, the German clo issued the Ust Id number retroactively in this particular case.
