In the fourth quarter of 2004, the German tax resident delivered €11,600 worth of goods to the German tax resident.
As part of the intergovernmental exchange of information, the German financial official asked for an examination of whether the aforementioned Czech tax evaders actually existed, since the alleged capital owner of the German tax evader had founded a number of bogus stocks in Germany.
In the course of the company's review of the transaction, the Czech Tax Authority confirmed the purchase of the goods.
According to the Czech tax payer, however, the goods were not delivered to the Czech Republic by Germany, but sold on in Germany in 2005.
The Czech tax collector presented evidence of the sale in January 2005.
The Czech tax payer was not registered as a tax payer in Germany and had not taxed the sale of the goods in question either in the Czech Republic or in Germany.
All of these facts pointed to tax evasion within Germany and the Czech tax official sent this information to the German tax administration in his response to the request for information.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the ncú found that the Czech tax collector had issued a supplementary tax return for the fourth quarter of 2004 on the basis of a tax audit, in which he declared, among other things, the value of the goods he had acquired from a German tax collector and at the same time asserted the right of the pre-tax deduction for the acquisition from other Member States.
In his Czech sales tax return, he did not report any sales tax on the sale of goods in Germany.
On the basis of a supplementary VAT return issued after the external audit, the Czech tax official determined the VAT liability unchanged.
According to Czech legislation, in this case, there was no purchase of goods from other Member States, as the goods were not shipped or transported to the Czech Republic from another Member State.
Thus, the Czech Financial official drew the wrong conclusion in the external audit.
The BRH found that the German tax official immediately after receiving the reply to the request for information, which showed that the goods had not left Germany, corrected the tax return of the German tax payer and demanded the payment of VAT worth 1,600 €.
In addition, the relevant Fa sent a control notice to the FA, which is responsible for the actual recipient of the goods, to ensure that the resale of these goods is properly taxed.
In the following cases, entrepreneurs declared intra-Community deliveries, which may not have been carried out:
18.
The Czech tax official received a request for information from the German Tax Administration on whether the Czech tax payer had purchased a car worth €47,400 from the German tax payer in February 2005.
The request for information was accompanied by a copy of the VAT registration certificate issued by the Czech tax payer.
A photocopy of the passport of the person who was supposed to have transferred the vehicle was attached as a further attachment.
In the course of his investigation, the Czech Financial official found that the passport was stolen, that the person named in it had not brought a vehicle into the Czech Republic and said that he had no contact with a German tax collector.
The VAT registration certificate, the copy of which was sent by the German side, was not issued by the Czech Financial Administration.
With this information, the Czech Financial Officer answered the request for information and said at the same time that he could not confirm the purchase of the car.
In a request to the local Czech financial officer, the nkú found that the Czech tax collector does not have his registered office at the address indicated in the Commercial Register and that the company's managing director is not available.
Following a tax complaint procedure for the tax period of February 2005, the Czech tax official determined the tax liability of the Czech tax payer with zero.
In the course of a further investigation, the Czech finance official found that the vehicle in question had been sold to another Czech person who had purchased it on the basis of an Internet advertisement.
The BRH found that the local German financial officer had rejected the claim of the German tax payer to exempt this delivery from VAT on the basis of the Czech response to the request for information.
19. In the course of an external audit, a German company was not able to clarify a difference of €3,000 between the value of the purchased goods indicated in the VAT return and the reported values from other Member States.
In the fourth quarter of 2004 and in the first quarter of 2005, a Czech tax collector should have delivered goods worth €89,424 to a German tax collector.
Since the acquisition declared by the German tax payer was not in line with the MIAS data, the German tax official asked for the verification of deliveries and their payment within the framework of the intergovernmental exchange of information.
In his reply to the request for information, the Czech Financial official said that the only managing director of the Czech company had been deleted from the commercial register on 8 July 2005 and that a new managing director had not yet been registered.
The German recipient of the goods was probably a relative of the shareholder of the Czech company.
The Czech tax collector issued a sales tax return and a ZM, which was signed after the CEO was removed from the commercial register by a person not authorized to do so, namely this shareholder of the company.
The accountant of the Czech tax payer told the Financial Officer that the owner of the capital had paid the payment received for the goods in euros into the company's account.
Receipts have not been issued.
In a request to the local Czech company, the ncú found that the financial officer had accepted the claim of the Czech tax payer for VAT exemption for deliveries of goods to other Member States, valued at CZK 1,326,307 in the first quarter of 2004 and CZK 1,416,180 in the first quarter of 2005.
The BRH found that the German tax official did not correct the sales tax return of the German acquirer, since in the meantime a German court had confirmed the insolvency of the German tax payer.
Since the previous external audit did not show any signs of tax fraud, there was no prospect of actually being able to charge a fixed VAT debt.
20. According to Mias data, in 2005, a German tax collector purchased goods from the Czech Republic worth €4,251,196, after which he purchased goods worth €43,274 the previous year.
The German tax authority did not explain the intra-Community acquisitions in its 2004 sales tax return or in the 2005.
In addition, he did not declare any value-related initial sales.
Due to these discrepancies, the German FA submitted a request for information regarding the fourth quarter of 2005 and the first quarter of 2006.
In the ZM for these two quarters, a Czech supplier reported intra-Community deliveries of goods with a total value of CZK 167,246,083.
On 6 September 2006, the request for information was received, in which the German side asked to check whether the delivery reported by the Czech tax payer had actually taken place.
In response to this request for information, the Czech Financial Administration said that the German request could not be complied with because the Czech company did not have a managing director (or other legal representative).
The documents provided to the ncú by the responsible financial officer show that, together with the managing director of the Czech Tax Office, a protocol was drawn up on 30 March 2006 on the start of the VAT audit for the fourth quarter of 2004 and the period from January to December 2005.
At the same time, the tax collector was asked by the tax official to submit all accounting and tax documents for this period, but he did not do so.
According to the Commercial Register, the term of office of the sole managing director expired on 16 May 2005 without the appointment of a new managing director.
The Czech tax collector has not issued any sales tax returns since April 2006.
As part of the parallel investigation, the ncú, in cooperation with the BRH, investigated several cases of intra-Community deliveries between the Czech Republic and Germany, which were not the subject of a prior exchange of information between the two countries.
The two courts of auditors exchanged information on the audited cases through the CLO of both countries.
21. A Czech company (UCR), which is not based in Germany, informed the Responsible Company (Chemnitz-Süd) that it wanted to do tax-related business in Germany.
Based on this information, the company was registered from June 2005, but did not receive a German USt-IdNr.
The (UCR) accepted an order from a Danish company (UdK) for the production of wind turbines and their delivery to Austria on behalf, at the risk and for the account of the Danish customer.
Due to insufficient production capacity, the Danish company passed on part of the order to a German tax payer (UDE) based in Germany.
The following figure shows the contractual relations and the transport route of the wind turbines:
According to German law, the place of performance of these transactions must be determined as described below:
- the Danish company (UdK) sent the wind turbines to Austria on its behalf, at its risk and for its own account.
Because of the installation, its delivery takes place in Austria, i.e. the delivery of the wind turbines is controllable in Austria.
- because the freight forwarder was commissioned by the Danish company (UdK) and the latter had the transport carried out on its own behalf, at its own risk and for its own account, the place of delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE) is where the transport started, i.e. in Germany.
Although the wind turbines were delivered to another EC member state (AU) and the recipient is registered as a tax resident in an EC member state (CR), no tax exemption could be claimed for the delivery of the German sub-contractor (UDE), since the EC member state for which the delivery was intended is different from the state of the Czech company 19.
Accordingly, the delivery is properly taxed in Germany and the Czech company (UCR) made the deduction in its VAT returns.
The place of delivery of the Czech company (UCR) also depends on the place where the transport started.
However, some of the wind turbines were transported from the Czech Republic and others from Germany.
- the delivery of wind turbines manufactured in the Czech Republic took place in the Czech Republic.
- the delivery of the remaining wind turbines manufactured in Germany took place in Germany.
Accordingly, the Czech company (UCR) delivered both intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic to Austria and intra-Community deliveries from Germany to Austria.
The BRH found that the Czech company (UCR) did not declare intra-Community deliveries in its German tax returns or in its ZM delivered to the German CLO.
Thus, the Czech company may have treated all its intra-Community deliveries uniformly as intra-Community deliveries from the Czech Republic.
The ncú found that (UCR) did not report intra-Community deliveries to Austria, but intra-Community deliveries to Denmark.
In order to ensure the taxation of intra-Community purchases in Austria, cooperation between at least four tax administrations (Austrian, Czech, Danish and German) would be required, although in this case there is no evidence of tax fraud or tax evasion.
In addition, the ncú and the BRH examined case designs to show the extent of differences between the information in the VAT returns and the MIAS data caused by the different Laws of 2004.
The cases examined also show that it takes some time for the tax payers and the tax authorities to apply the new legal regulations:
22. In its ZM for the second, third and fourth quarters of 2004, a Czech tax-exempt supply of goods with a total value of 792,977,452 CZK was reported to a German tax payer.
In the same period, another Czech tax collector reported in his ZM intra-Community deliveries to another German tax collector in the total value of 18,157,265 CZK.
From the information provided by the BRH TO THE nkú, it emerged that both were electricity supplies.
Both Czech tax payers took into account the above-mentioned deliveries in their ZM in accordance with Czech Law No. 235 / 2004, which was in force in 2004.
During a further examination of these transactions, an nkú Audit Group found that in 2004, different legal regulations governing the supply and purchase of electrical energy were in force between the Czech Republic and Germany.
While in the Czech Republic, tax payers declared the supply of electrical energy as intra-Community goods, in accordance with the provisions of Law No. 235 / 2004 in force in 2004, according to the German legislation in force in 2004, it was not an intra-Community purchase of goods, but taxable and tax-free sales in Germany.
The differences in the legal regulations were eliminated in the Czech Republic by the adoption of the Law no. 635 / 2004, which changed some tax regulations with effect from 1 January 2005.
23. During the examination of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions in cooperation with the BRH, it was further established that a Czech tax collector in his ZM for the first and fourth quarters of 2005 intra-Community deliveries to a German tax payer for a total value of CZK 240,411,163 and another Czech tax collector in his ZM for the same period intra-Community deliveries to another German tax resident for a value of CZK 263,470.776 CZK declared.
Information provided by the BRH TO THE nkú showed that both were electric energy supplies.
According to the wording of Act No. 235 / 2004, which applies from 1 January 2005, the place of performance for the supply of electrical energy is the place of performance where the acquirer has his legal domicile, his place of business or his place of business for which the supply is made.
Therefore, the Czech tax authorities were not allowed to specify the electricity supplies in their ZM for 2005.
The fact that both tax payers treated the supply of electrical energy in their ZM as intra-Community supplies resulted in a difference of CZK 503,881,939 in MIAs.
Final comment
The cooperation achieved the objectives of the BRH AND THE nkú.
Both courts of auditors gained in-depth knowledge of VAT administration systems in the Czech Republic and Germany.
The cooperation revealed differences in the two systems and in the legal regulations governing the VAT administration.
During the parallel tests, interesting cases of intra-Community deliveries or acquisitions were revealed.
Some of them are worth further observation.
On the basis of the audit results, both audit offices drew up recommendations for the management of VAT.
The follow-up of these recommendations in the form of a review should be part of the further observation.
The new experience and knowledge gained through the cooperation between the two courts of auditors is the basis for the successful execution of future audits in the area of turnover tax administration.
